<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1915-04-27T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1915-04-27T00:00:00-05:00" n="298" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d298">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">710.11/203½</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">President <persName type="from">Wilson</persName> to
                                the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                            </hi>
                        </head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1915-04-27">
                                    <hi rend="italic">27 April, 1915</hi>
                                </date>.</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">My Dear Mr. Secretary</hi>: This seems to me
                                excellent.<note n="10" xml:id="d298fn1">Draft of letter to the
                                Chilean Ambassador; for the letter as sent, see <hi rend="italic">infra.</hi>
                            </note> I agree with you that it is wise to be explicit and that it is
                            well to put these views in writing, as you have done.</p>
                        <p>I think it would be wise, however, to state that the provisions as to
                            territory as you restate them in this letter are not definitively
                            proposed (for we have not yet shown them to Argentine and Brazil, upon
                            whose cooperation we are depending) but are formulated by way of
                            suggestion of what we would be quite willing to discuss, if in that form
                            they commended themselves to the Chilean government.</p>
                        <p>Faithfully Yours,</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>W. W.</signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>